@node Intro "Introduction"

  @{b}@{u}Introduction to MultiRen - The Ultimate Renamer@{uu}@{ub}

   This program is for renaming, usually multiple files, hense the
   name, using specially designed Tools, or just manually using the
   string gadget.

   One great thing with MultiRen is that no files are actually
   renamed during your work until you decide so and then press
   Rename in the @{"main window" link mainwin}.

   Another great thing is that you can save the list of filenames
   and their states if you want to continue the next day or maybe
   just to save the list as a backup so that you can undo, i.e.
   reload the list, if a tool didn't do quite what you wanted.

   You can also save the list as a plain text file for use as f.ex.
   a play list, batch file or whatever. You can customize this
   text file in very flexible ways. See the @{"Export list as text.." link exporttext}.

   MultiRen also support plugins that can do virtually anything once
   created! Currently there is only a few plugins available but they
   can extract the names out of MP3s, 8SVX samples, picture, convert
   UTF8 file name etc!

   It if also possible to edit and set file comments on your file,
   and you can use the plugins for this as well.

   The program support filenames of up to 512 characters excluding
   path.


@endnode

@node Reqs "Requirements"

  @{b}@{u}What you need to be able to run MultiRen@{uu}@{ub}

   OS version 37+

   MUI - Magical User Interface v3.x+
     NListview.mcc
     NList.mcc
     BetterString.mcc
     TextEditor.mcc

   ASL.library  v38+
   MathIEEESingbas.library v33+

   A @{"keyfile" link KeyMail} for full functionality.


@endnode

@node Inst "Installation"

  @{b}@{u}How to get MultiRen into your system!@{uu}@{ub}

   Just double-click on the Install icon, or:

   Copy the whole directory with all subdirectories, possibly
   without the developer directory if you do not plan on
   developing plugins yourself, to anywhere on your harddisk.

   When this is done, send @{"me" link Author} an e-mail with your name to be
   in the registration field and ask for a keyfile.
   When you receive your keyfile, put it in S:, ENVARC: or
   the same directory as MultiRen itself.

   Nothing more than this is required except for having what's
   in the @{"Requirements" link Reqs} page.


@endnode

@node Usage "Usage"

  @{b}@{u}Usage of MultiRen - The Ultimate Renamer@{uu}@{ub}

   This program might not be the easiest to begin with as it has
   many different settings and features but I suggest that you
   try it out if you want a good and flexible renaming program,
   maybe along with this guide by your side!

   I could mention that I personally find the Renplacer and the
   File Cleaner tools the most useful, and sometimes the Adaptor.

   The program also got bubble help for about everything in the GUI.
   And if the bubble help in not sufficient you can always press Help
   on your keyboard and get this guide opened to the page of the
   window that is active. This however requires that MultiRen.guide
   is in the same directory as MultiRen itself.

   Note that only buttons with @{b}bold@{ub} text does any actual change
   to you files (in the program that is, not in this guide)! These
   button are currently; @{u}Rename@{uu} and @{u}Undo rename@{uu} in the main window
   and @{u}Set Comments@{uu} in both the @{"File Comment" link comment} tool and the
   main window.

   You can start MultiRen with files as arguments or start it while
   shift-clicking on icons in Workbench if you like. Drag'n'drop also
   works.


   @{u}About the main window@{uu}

    It is in the main window all your files reside, and it is only
    from here you can do the actual renaming of your files.

    @{"Main window          " link mainwin}
    @{"Main windows menu    " link mainmenu}

    @{"Preferences window   " link prefs}

    @{"Export list as text.." link exporttext}
    @{"Import a text file.. " link importtext}


   @{u}About the extension tools@{uu}

    The tools is what makes this program powerful!  With all their
    features you virtually never have to touch your filenames
    "manually".

    @{"Adaptor..         " link adaptor}
    @{"Extension Editor.." link extension}
    @{"File Cleaner..    " link filecleaner}
    @{"File Comment..    " link comment}
    @{"Numberer..        " link numberer}
    @{"Renplacer..       " link renplacer} -> The plugins are used from here!
    @{"Sort..            " link sort}

    @{"The tools common menu" link toolsmenu}


@endnode

@node mainwin "The main window"

 @{b}@{u}The main window@{uu}@{ub}

  The main window is where the list of your files reside and alot of
  buttons for managing the list. This is also the only window that
  has the button for perform the actual rename of your files.

  See also the @{"main windows menu" link mainmenu} which have alot more functions
  for managing the list and other stuff in the program.

  You can also drop icons (files or directories) on this window
  and add files or directories or contents of directories.

  @{i}The main lister@{ui}

    This is the list where all files for renaming reside.
    You can drag'n'drop files in this list to get them in
    any order you like. You will have to drag the file(s)
    out from the side of the list to get a grip, otherwise
    you will just multi-select the files.
    Drag'n'drop can be useful if you're making a playlist
    or something!

    The columns in the lister (from left):
      @{fg fill}E@{fg text}/@{fg fill}D@{fg text}: This will tell if the remind should be @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled for
           the tools to play with, otherwise @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isabled.
           You can toggle the @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled/@{fg fill}D@{fg text}isabled state by clicking
           on a file in this column.
      @{fg fill}C@{fg text}:   This shows if the @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} has been @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged in
           any way, i.e if it is different to @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub}.
      @{fg fill}R@{fg text}/@{fg fill}@{b}F@{ub}@{fg text}: The R tells that the file was successfully @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed
           from @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub} to @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} and the file now
           actually is called what is in the @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} field.
           An @{fg fill}F@{fg text} means that the file @{fg fill}F@{fg text}ailed to rename and
           that it is still called what is in the @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub}
           field.
      @{fg fill}c@{fg text}/@{fg fill}@{b}C@{ub}@{fg text}/@{fg fill}@{i}F @{ui}@{fg text}
           This column is for the file comments.
           No letter in this column means that the file has no filecomment.
           A 'c' (lower case) means that the file has an unchanged file comment.
           A '@{b}C@{ub}' (upper case fat) means that the file has a comment and that
           is has been changed. NOTE: The file comment doesn't have an "old comment"
           like the filename so even if you change the comment and then change
           it back it would still be marked changed.
           An '@{i}F @{ui}' means that setting the filecomment failed.

      @{b}@{u}Path@{uu}@{ub}:     This is the paths for the files. You can hide this
                column from the @{"prefs" link prefs} if you want to.
      @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub}: This is the original name of the files. You can
                always use the menu and restore the files in the
                @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} to this original names.
      @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub}: This is the list of the new names that you can
                Let the tools change for you or you can change them
                manually with the string below this list.
                If you want to use the string gadget to edit the filename
                by hand you have to press in this column.
      @{b}@{u}Comment@{uu}@{ub}:  This column shows the filecomment for the current
                file. This can be made visible from the @{"prefs" link prefs}
                if you want to.
                If you want to use the string gadget to edit the comment
                by hand you have to press in this column.
      @{b}@{u}Length@{uu}@{ub}:   This will not show the length of the files but the
                length of the filenames in characters. This can be
                made visible from the @{"prefs" link prefs} if you want to.

  @{b}Add@{ub}
    @{u}File(s)@{uu}
      Add one or more files using an ASL-requester.
    @{u}Directory@{uu}
      Add all files within one directory.
    @{u}Recursive dirs@{uu}
      Add all files in one directory and all its subdirectories.
    @{u}Load a list@{uu}
      This opens an ASL-requester asking you to pick a previously
      saved list. You can also load a textfile with filenames here
      too, but usually you would load a .mrl file. (mrl = MultiRen List)

    When you are adding files you can set if you only want to
    add files that have certain lengths. See @{"prefs" link prefs} and the
    page @{fg shine}Length restrictions@{fg text} for more information.


  @{b}Remove@{ub}
    This will remove the active file if no files are selected,
    or all selected files except the active one.

  @{b}Clear list@{ub}
    Remove all files from the list.

  @{b}Enable@{ub}
    This will mark all selected files, or the active file as @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled.
    Other files will not be touched.

  @{b}Disable@{ub}
    This will mark all selected files, or the active file as @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isabled.
    Other files will not be touched.

  @{b}Select all@{ub}
    This will select all files in the list.

  @{b}Restore@{ub}
    This will copy @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub} to @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} of the
    active file (the one whose @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} or @{b}@{u}Comment@{uu}@{ub} is
    present in the string gadget) in the list, if it was @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged.

  @{b}Undo@{ub}
    This will undo the last thing you wrote in the string
    gadget as long as you did not select another file.

  @{b}<checkmark>@{ub}
    Selects wether this file is @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled or @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isabled.

  @{b}<string gadget>@{ub}
    This is where you manually can change the name or filecomment
    if you want. Use the arrow keys to move up and down in the
    list when this string gadget is active if you don't want to
    use the mouse to scroll!..
    This string has spacebar as hotkey for most convenience.

  @{b}<number field>@{ub}
    This shows the length of the current filename.
    @{i}Italic @{ui}means that the length of the filename is out
    of range according to what is specified in @{"prefs" link prefs},
    page "Length restrictions".
    This will be hidden if you make the column Length in
    the list visible.

  @{b}Rename@{ub}
    This is the *magic button* that will use the list and
    rename your files from @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub} to @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub}!
    If it was successful, the files will be marked @{fg fill}R@{fg text} for
    @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed, otherwise they will be marked @{fg fill}F@{fg text} for @{fg fill}F@{fg text}ailed.
    NOTE: Only files marked @{fg fill}E@{fg text} for @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled and @{fg fill}C@{fg text} for
          @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged will be renamed!

  @{b}Undo rename@{ub}
    This is also a *magic button* but it will rename files
    back to their original (@{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} to @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub}) name
    if they are marked @{fg fill}R@{fg text} for @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed and @{fg fill}E@{fg text} for @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled.

  @{b}Set Comments@{ub}
    This is the button that sets the file comments to your
    actual files. Only files marked @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled and @{fg fill}@{b}C@{ub}@{fg text} (bold 'C' for changed
    comment) will be set. The same button can also be found
    in the @{"File Comment" link comment} tool.

  @{b}Tools@{ub}

    @{fg shine}@{u}Open all tools@{uu}@{fg text}
      This will open all tool-windows.
    @{fg shine}@{u}Close all tools@{uu}@{fg text}
      This will close all tool-windows.

    @{u}Adaptor@{uu}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Adaptor" link adaptor} tool.
      This is a tool for shorting down or prolonging filenames
      that is too long or too short. This is done in a "smart"
      way as it always tries to keep the filename as readable
      and recognizable as possible.
    @{u}Extension Editor@{uu}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Extension Editor" link extension} tool.
      With this you can change files extensions, change
      mod.songname to songname.mod and much more.
    @{u}File Cleaner@{uu}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"File Cleaner" link filecleaner} tool.
      This is for cleaning up ugly looking filenames and
      remove unwanted characters.
    @{u}File Comment@{uu}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"File Comment" link comment} tool.
      With this you can edit the filecomment of your files.
    @{u}Numberer@{uu}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Numberer" link numberer} tool.
      With this you can create file series in a very easy
      and flexible way.
    @{u}Renplacer@{uu}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Renplacer" link renplacer} tool.
      With this you can rename file by pattern, or replace
      parts of filenames with something else.
      There is also a Find function.
    @{u}Sort@{uu}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"sort-window" link sort}.
      With this you can sort the list by a numerous of ways,
      automatically after using tools or manually.

    @{fg fill}@{u}Export as text@{uu}@{fg text}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Export as text" link exporttext} window
      where you can save the list of filenames to a textfile.
    @{fg fill}@{u}Import a textfile@{uu}@{fg text}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Import a textfile" link importtext} window
      where you can pick a textfile to replace your filenames in
      the list with.


  @{b}Prefs..@{ub}
    This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Preferences and Global settings" link prefs}
    window.

  @{b}Quit@{ub}
    This will quit the program and ask you to save the list if any
    item is @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged.


@endnode

@node exporttext "Export list as text.."

 @{b}@{u}Export list as text..@{uu}@{ub}

  This is the window which will open when you are going to export
  the list as a text file. It gives good possibilities for you to
  decide exactly what and how to save the list.

  There are more preciely two ways of composing your text file:
  The simple way and the custom way:

  @{u}Simple@{uu}

    @{fg shine}Old name@{fg text}
      @{b}Exclude Old name@{ub}:   Do not save @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub}'s at all
      @{b}Path only@{ub}:          Save @{b}@{u}Path@{uu}@{ub} only. (This is the same for
                          Old and New name)
      @{b}Filename only@{ub}:      Save @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub} without path
      @{b}Filename with path@{ub}: Save @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub} with path

    @{fg shine}New name@{fg text}
      @{b}Exclude New name@{ub}:   Do not save @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub}'s at all
      @{b}Path only@{ub}:          Save @{b}@{u}Path@{uu}@{ub} only. (This is the same for
                          Old and New name)
      @{b}Filename only@{ub}:      Save @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} without path
      @{b}Filename with path@{ub}: Save @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} with path

    Here you have 3 string gadgets. These strings are there so
    that you can put commands or something along with your
    filenames when you export the list.
    Old and New between the strings stands for @{b}@{u}Old name@{ub}@{uu} and
    @{b}@{u}New name@{ub}@{uu}, i.e. this is where the Old- and New name will be
    placed relative to these strings.

    Example of making a backup script:
     You enter "Copy " in the first string and
     " TO MyBackupUnit:backup/ ALL QUIET" in the middle.
     Set @{fg shine}Old name@{fg text} to @{b}Filename with path@{ub} and @{fg shine}New name@{fg text} to
     @{b}Exclude New name@{ub} and the result should be:

      @{fg shine}Copy unit:path/my_first_oldname TO MyBackup_unit:backup/ ALL QUIET
      Copy unit:path/the_second_oldname TO MyBackup_unit:backup/ ALL QUIET
      .....@{fg text}


     Got it??
     If not, try it out yourself :-)


    @{b}Save on separate lines@{ub}
      This will save @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub} and @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} on separate lines if
      both are saved.

    @{b}Save in columns@{ub}
      This will save @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub} and @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} in vertical columns.
      Example:
        @{fg shine}Short old name.jpg                  First new name.jpg
        An old name that is much longer.mp3 Second new name.mp3
        .....                               ...@{fg text}

      Instead of:
        @{fg shine}Short old name.jpg First new name.jpg
        An old name that is much longer.mp3 Second new name.mp3
        ..... ...@{fg text}

    @{b}"Quote" filenames@{ub}
      This will put quote signs around every filename, including
      it's path if any. Useful if you plan to make you own filelist
      of some kind and got spaces in some filenames or paths.

    @{b}"Quote" paths@{ub}
      If you have set either @{b}@{u}Old name@{ub}@{uu} or @{b}@{u}New name@{ub}@{uu} to Path only you
      can use this switch if you want "quotes" around paths too.


  @{u}Custom@{uu}

    Here you have great possibilities to customize the output a lot.
    You can create multi-line entries for each file which allows
    for the possibility to create batch scripts directly from within
    MultiRen.

    You could even create HTML output, for example the contents of a
    table with your files and associated information that you could
    paste into you homepage or similar.

    You could also output all your file on one single line if you
    omit a %\\ at the end of your line.

    @{b}Example@{ub}
      If you press this button the selected file in the main list
      will be used as an example of what your custom strings will
      look like.
      Note: If you use a multi-line custon string (i.e. containing
      many %\\ (percent sign followed by one backslash)) and the text
      object below this button and the string is too small it will
      print text outside of itself onto the other gadgets leaving
      graphics garbage. This is harmless but doesn't look too nice.
      It's bug in MUI's TextObject class.

    @{i}string@{ui}
      In this field you enter a formatted string that will be the
      template for how your exported file list will look like.
      You can pick formatting switches from the pop-down menu to
      the right.

      The switches are as follows:
       %o - Will insert the current Old name
       %n - Will insert the current New name
       %p - Will insert the current path ending @{b}with@{ub} ":" or "/"
       %c - Will insert the current comment
       %e - Will insert the extension of the New name
       %E - Will insert the extension of the Old name
       %O - Will insert the current Old name without its extension
       %N - Will insert the current New name without its extension
       %lf - Will give the file length of the current file in bytes
       %lF - Will give the file length in bytes with thousand separators
       %lk - Will give the file length of the current file in kilobytes
       %lK - Will give the file length in kilobytes with thousand separators
       %lm - Will give the file length of the current file in megabytes
       %lo - Will give the current Old name length
       %ln - Will give the current New name length
       %ly - Will give the current year as a 4-digit number
       %lp - Will give the last directory in the path @{b}without@{ub} ":" or "/"
       %s - Will give the current second in two digits
       %m - Will give the current minute in two digits
       %h - Will give the current hour in tw digits
       %w - Will give the current week day. Ex. Monday
       %D - Will give the current day of the month
       %M - Will give the current month as a number
       %Y - Will give the current year as a 2-digit number
       %fs - Will give the filedates second in two digits
       %fm - Will give the filedates minute in two digits
       %fh - Will give the filedates hour in tw digits
       %fw - Will give the filedates week day. Ex. Monday
       %fD - Will give the filedates day of the month
       %fM - Will give the filedates month as a number
       %fY - Will give the filedates year as a 2-digit number
       %% - Will safely insert a %-char
       %[ - Will safely insert a [-char
       %] - Will safely insert a ]-char
       %\\ - Will insert a linefeed. You probably want to insert
            a %\\ at the end of your string to prevent the whole
            file to end up on one single line.

      After every switch (except %%, %[, %] and %\\) you can write
      [<offset>;<length>] so that you may pick just a part of a
      filename or something when you are composing your file. If
      <length> is omitted then the string will be read to the end.
      If length is negative, this amount of characters will be
      skipped at the end or the string.

      Example:
        Let's say that we have Old name's that looks like this:
          @{fg shine}My vacation 03 - Swimming.jpg
          My vacation 04 - Hiking.jpg@{fg text}

        Then we could write..:
          @{fg shine}%o[17,-4], Pic no.%o[12,2] - %[Date: %D/%M-%ly%]%\\@{fg text}

        ...and get a result something like this:
          @{fg shine}Swimming, Pic no.03 - [Date: 14/6-2001]
          Hiking, Pic no.04 - [Date: 14/6-2001]
          @{fg text}

        Note the -4 in %o[17,-4] how it cuts the ".jpg" extension.

      Another example using a multi-line export:
        Let's say that we have two files:
          @{fg shine}Billy Joel - My Life.mp3
          Billy Joel - Piano Man.mp3@{fg text}

          (You can ofcourse have any number of files.)

        Then we could write..:        
          @{fg shine}File: "%o"%\\Size: %lKkB%\\Date [%fY-%fM-%fD]%\\Comment:%c%\\%\\@{fg text}

        ...and get a result something like this:
          @{fg shine}File: "Billy Joel - My Life.mp3"
          Size: 4.428kB
          Date [02-07-23]
          Comment:The Ultimate Collection {CD1}

          File: "Billy Joel - Piano Man.mp3"
          Size: 5.280kB
          Date [02-07-23]
          Comment:The Ultimate Collection {CD1}
          @{fg text}

        A very simple yet effective way of creating an index file
        for a large directory of files. This way you could even
        create the body for a html-page which could have taken days
        to do by hand!

      Example using the %t in two places:
      Let's say we have four filenames which have different sizes:

        @{fg shine}ID3-Tag.mrp@{fg text}
        @{fg shine}QuotedPrintable.mrp@{fg text}
        @{fg shine}QuotedPrintable.readme@{fg text}
        @{fg shine}Substitute.list@{fg text}

      Then we could write:
        @{fg shine}%o%t - (%lF) %t:Draft from plugins directory@{fg text}

      ..and get:

        @{fg shine}ID3-Tag.mrp            - (7.672) :Draft from plugins directory@{fg text}
        @{fg shine}QuotedPrintable.mrp    - (3.052) :Draft from plugins directory@{fg text}
        @{fg shine}QuotedPrintable.readme - (981)   :Draft from plugins directory@{fg text}
        @{fg shine}Substitute.list        - (29)    :Draft from plugins directory@{fg text}

      ..in very nice columns.


    @{b}Store  Remove@{ub}
      These two buttons is used to store or remove custom strings to or
      from the memo list for the Text Export window. You can get a stored
      string by clicking on the popdown button at the right of these
      buttons and then select one of your stored strings.

      This feature is very nice if you often use more than one custom
      string and don't want to retype it all the time.

      If the "Save memo lists" is set in the prefs this will be saved
      immediately when you use Store or Remove.

    @{b}Use two digits for date@{ub}
      With this set, the day (%D, %fD) and month (%M, fM) will
      always be printed as a 2-digit number. I would make sense to
      unselect this if you want to show a date as 3/7 instead of
      03/07. The year is always 2 (or 4) digits.


  @{b}Save as..@{ub}
    This will open an ASL-requester asking you to pick a filename
    to save this text to. If the Simple page is displayed, the file
    will be saved using the settings on the Simple page, else the
    custom string will be parsed and saved instead.

  @{b}Save@{ub}
    This will save the list to the last saved file. If the Simple
    page is displayed, the file will be saved using the settings
    on the Simple page, else the custom string will be parsed and
    saved instead.

  @{b}Close@{ub}
    This closes the window.


@endnode

@node importtext "Map a textfile on your filenames"

 @{b}@{u}Map a file to your filenames@{uu}@{ub}

  This is the window which will open when you are going to import
  a textfile to replace your old filenames.
  Using this is sort of the opposite of the @{"export" link exporttext} function!

  The mapping works like this:
  The first line in the textfile will be applied to the first @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled
  file in the list, the second line in the textfile to the second
  @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled file in the list and so on. Very simple!

  Ofcourse there are options if you f.ex do not want to entirely
  replace your old filenames/filecomments. Maybe you do not want
  to start to read at the first line in the textfile you are
  importing, maybe you want to preserve the extensions you have
  on your old filenames, maybe you want to preserve the beginning
  of the filename..?  Well, all that is possible..!


  @{i}<stringgadget> @{ui}
    This is the textfile that will be imported.

  @{b}Start read from line@{ub}
    Here you can set from what line in the textfile you want to start
    to read. 1 is the first line.

  @{b}Number of lines to read@{ub}
    Here you can set how many lines you want to read from the files.
    0 means to read to the end of the input file or to the end of the
    list of filenames in MultiRen.

  @{b}Insertion offset@{ub}
    Here you can set how many characters from the left in the filenames/
    filecomments you want the text-lines inserted. Nice if you have
    numbered files (with the number in the beginning of the filename) and
    want to preserve them.
    "End", which is default for this slider, means that if @{b}Insert text, do
    not replace@{ub} is selected, the text-lines will be appended at the end
    of current filenames/filecomments (with preserved extensions or not)
    and if it is not selected, the whole filename/filecomment will be
    replaced (with preserved extensions or not).

  @{b}Disable files after the mapping@{ub}
    This is useful if you don't want the files that have been mapped
    to change anymore. Also useful if you intend to pick new files
    to continue down the list, as mapping is only done on @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled files.

  @{b}Preserve extensions (no effect on comments)@{ub}
    Useful if the filenames in your textfile does not have extensions
    but your current filenames does and you want to keep them.
    This is ignored when you map to filecomments.

  @{b}Insert text, do not replace@{ub}
    Generally, "Import a text file" is used to replace old filenames
    but with this you can prevent that and add the filenames in the
    textfile to your current filenames/filecomments instead of replacing
    them. @{b}Preserve extensions@{ub} works here as well.

  @{b}Map over filenames@{ub}
    This will map the textfile to your @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub}'s.

  @{b}Map over filecomments@{ub}
    This will map the textfile to your @{b}@{u}File Comment@{uu}@{ub}'s.

  @{b}Close@{ub}
    This closes the window.


@endnode

@node mainmenu "The menu of the main window"

 @{b}@{u}The menu of the main window@{uu}@{ub}

  This is the menu which will become available when the main
  window is active.

  The Edit section contains list managing functions.


  @{b}@{u}Project@{uu}@{ub}

    @{b}Open/Refresh Info window@{ub}
      This will open/refresh the little info-window that shows some info
      about the files in the list. It shows How many files there are,
      how many is enabled/disabled, longest and shortes filename etc.

    @{b}Open Substitute generator@{ub}
      This will open the substitute generator that is used by some
      plugins to filter out unwanted characters.

    @{b}Preferences..@{ub}
      This will open/close the @{"Preferences and Global settings" link prefs}
      window.

    @{b}MUI settings..@{ub}
      This will open the standard MUI settings window fro this program.

    @{b}Snapshot all windows@{ub}
      This will do a MUI snapshot on all windows in MultiRen, including
      all closed ones. This way you can organize all windows as you like
      and just use this option instead of pressing the snapshot gadget
      in every single window. You might not even have that gadget activated.

    @{b}Save settings@{ub}
      This will save all global settings in MultiRen. Practical if you
      change something in a Tool and do not want to open the Prefs-window
      just to press Save there.

    @{b}Easy registering..@{ub}
      This opens a window with a simple registration-form in it that you
      can copy with your mouse and past into you mail program and then
      send to me to get a keyfile.

    @{b}About@{ub}
      Opens an about-requester for MultiRen.

    @{b}OnyxSoft@{ub}
      Opens an info-requester for OnyxSoft.

    @{b}Quit@{ub}
      This will quit the program. If there is files in the list a quit-
      requester will pop up. If you find that requester annoying then
      just clear the list before you quit.


  @{b}@{u}List@{uu}@{ub}

    @{b}Add@{ub}
      @{u}File(s)@{uu}
        Add one or more files using an ASL-requester.
      @{u}Directory@{uu}
        Add all files within one directory.
      @{u}Recursive dirs@{uu}
        Add all files in one directory and all it's subdirectories.

      When you are adding files you can set if you only want to
      add files that have certain lengths. See @{"prefs" link prefs} and the
      page @{fg shine}Length restrictions@{fg text} for more info.


    @{b}Remove@{ub}
      This will remove the active file if no files are selected
      or all selected files except the active on.

    @{b}Clear list@{ub}
      Remove all files from the list.

    @{b}Save the list..@{ub}
      This will open an ASL-requester for you so that you can save
      the list (and all it's parameters) so that you f.ex can
      contine to work on the list another day or something.
      It's also good if you have renamed a couple of files and
      may want to save their original names as security if you
      might be unhappy with the new filenames some day :)

    @{b}Load a list..@{ub}
      This opens an ASL-requester asking you to pick a previously
      saved list. You can also load a textfile with filenames here
      too, but usually you would load a .mrl file. (mrl = MultiRen List)

    @{"Export list as text.." link exporttext}

    @{"Import a text file.." link importtext}

    @{b}Verify files@{ub}
      This will scan the main lister and test if all files really
      exist on disk or not.

      For files that exist the file date will be reread to allow
      sorting on file date. Useful if the date have been updated
      on disk, or if the list was saved using an earlier version
      than 1.70 of MultiRen which did not save file dates in the
      list.


  @{b}@{u}Edit@{uu}@{ub}

    All actions in this menu is take upon the files in the main lister
    depending on their parameters.

    @{b}Remove@{ub}
      @{u}Disabled file(s)@{uu}: This will remove all files marked @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isabled.
      @{u}Changed file(s)@{uu}:  This will remove all files marked @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged.
      @{u}Renamed file(s)@{uu}:  This will remove all files marked @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed.
      @{u}Failed file(s)@{uu}:   This will remove all files marked @{fg fill}F@{fg text}ailed.

    @{b}Keep@{ub}
      @{u}selected file(s)@{uu}: This removes all files not selected.
      @{u}Disabled file(s)@{uu}: This removes all files not marked @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isabled.
      @{u}Changed file(s)@{uu}:  This removes all files not marked @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged.
      @{u}Renamed file(s)@{uu}:  This removes all files not marked @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed.
      @{u}Failed file(s)@{uu}:   This removes all files not marked @{fg fill}F@{fg text}ailed.

    @{b}Enable only@{ub}
      @{u}all file(s)@{uu}:      This will mark all file @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled.
      @{u}selected file(s)@{uu}: This will @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nable all files that are selected
                        in the main lister and @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isable all others.
      @{u}Changed file(s)@{uu}:  This will @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nable all files that are @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged
                        in the main lister and @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isable all others.
      @{u}Renamed file(s)@{uu}:  This will @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nable all files that has been
                        @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed and @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isable all others.
      @{u}Failed file(s)@{uu}:   This will @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nable all files @{fg fill}F@{fg text}ailed to rename
                        and @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isable all others.

    @{b}Invert En/Disabling@{ub}
      This will make all files that are @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isabled @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled and all
      @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled files @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isabled.

    @{b}For all Enabled files@{ub}
      @{b}Update Renamed file(s)@{ub}
        This will copy the @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} to the @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub} for all
        files that has been successfully @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed.
        This will only be done on files that are also marked @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled.

      @{b}Restore Changed file(s)@{ub}
        This will copy the @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub} to the @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} for all
        files that are @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged. This is good if you have used a
        tool that didn't really do what you expected.
        This will only be done on files that are also marked @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled.

      @{b}Changed file(s) are Renamed@{ub}
        This is a special poke-thing. It will force MultiRen to relabel
        all files that are marked @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged to be marked @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed instead.
        Use this if you have edited a list, then saved it, then renamed
        the files. And now at a later state you reload the saved list
        but all files are marked @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged but are actually @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed.

      @{b}Renamed file(s) are Changed@{ub}
        This is a special poke-thing. It will force MultiRen to relabel
        all files that are marked @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed to be marked @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged instead.
        Use this if you have edited a list, then renamed the files, then
        saved the list. And now at a later state you reload the saved list
        but all files are marked @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed but are actually just @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged.


      @{b}Re-read file comments@{ub}
        This will re-read the file comments from the files. Sort of like
        an undo function.

    @{b}Pick new path@{ub}
      This will let you change the path for the selected files in
      the main lister. Useful if you have a saved list but you have
      moved the files that the list contains.


  @{b}@{u}Tools@{uu}@{ub}

    @{b}Adaptor@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Adaptor" link adaptor} tool.
      This is a tool for shorting down or prolonging filenames
      that is too long or too short. This is done in a "smart"
      way as it always tries to keep the filename as readable
      and recognizable as possible.
    @{b}Extension Editor@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Extension Editor" link extension} tool.
      With this you can change files extensions, change
      mod.songname to songname.mod and much more.
    @{b}File Cleaner@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"File Cleaner" link filecleaner} tool.
      This is for cleaning up ugly looking filenames and
      remove unwanted characters.
    @{b}File Comment@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"File Comment" link comment} tool.
      With this you can edit the filecomment of your files.
    @{b}Numberer@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Numberer" link numberer} tool.
      With this you can create file series in a very easy
      and flexible way.
    @{b}Renplacer@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Renplacer" link renplacer} tool.
      With this you can rename file by pattern, or replace
      parts of filenames with something else.
      There is also a Find function.
    @{b}Sort@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"sort-window" link sort}.
      With this you can sort the list by a numerous of ways,
      automatically after using tools or manually.

    @{b}Open all tools@{ub}
      This will open all tool-windows.
    @{b}Close all tools@{ub}
      This will close all tool-windows.


  @{b}@{u}Visible columns@{uu}@{ub}

    @{b}Path@{ub}
      Show/hide the path column in the main lister.

    @{b}Old name@{ub}
      Show/hide the Old name column in the main lister.

    @{b}File Comment@{ub}
      Show/hide the File Comment column in the main lister.

    @{b}Filename length@{ub}
      Show/hide the filename length column in the main lister.


@endnode

@node toolsmenu "The common menu for the tools"

 @{b}@{u}The common menu for the tools@{uu}@{ub}

  This is the menu which will become available when a tool-
  window is active.

  This menu section is similar to the @{"main window menu" link mainmenu} but
  without the Edit menu and some others..


  @{b}@{u}Project@{uu}@{ub}

    @{b}Open/Refresh Info window@{ub}
      This will open/refresh the little info-window that shows some info
      about the files in the list. It shows how many files there are,
      how many is enabled/disabled, longest and shortes filename etc.

    @{b}Open Substitute generator@{ub}
      This will open the substitute generator that is used by some
      plugins to filter out unwanted characters.

    @{b}Preferences..@{ub}
      This will open/close the @{"Preferences and Global settings" link prefs}
      window.

    @{b}MUI settings..@{ub}
      This will open the standard MUI settings window fro this program.

    @{b}Main window to front@{ub}
      This will bring the main window to front of all tool windows.

    @{b}Snapshot all windows@{ub}
      This will do a MUI snapshot on all windows in MultiRen, including
      all closed ones. This way you can organize all windows as you like
      and just use this option instead of pressing the snapshot gadget
      in every single window. You might not even have that gadget activated.

    @{b}Save settings@{ub}
      This will save all global settings in MultiRen. Practical if you
      change something in a Tool and do not want to open the Prefs-window
      just to press Save there.

    @{b}Easy registering..@{ub}
      This opens a window with a simple registration-form in it that you
      can copy with you mouse and past into you mail program and then
      send to me to get a keyfile.

    @{b}About@{ub}
      Opens an about-requester for MultiRen.

    @{b}Onyxsoft@{ub}
      Opens an info-requester for Onyxsoft.

    @{b}Quit@{ub}
      This will quit the program and ask you to save the list
      if any item is @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged.


  @{b}@{u}Tools@{uu}@{ub}

    @{b}Adaptor@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Adaptor" link adaptor} tool.
      This is a tool for shorting down or prolonging filenames
      that is too long or too short. This is done in a "smart"
      way as it always tries to keep the filename as readable
      and recognizable as possible.
    @{b}Extension Editor@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Extension Editor" link extension} tool.
      With this you can change files extensions, change
      mod.songname to songname.mod and much more.
    @{b}File Cleaner@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"File Cleaner" link filecleaner} tool.
      This is for cleaning up ugly looking filenames and
      remove unwanted characters.
    @{b}File Comment@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"File Comment" link comment} tool.
      With this you can edit the filecomment of your files.
    @{b}Numberer@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Numberer" link numberer} tool.
      With this you can create file series in a very easy
      and flexible way.
    @{b}Renplacer@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"Renplacer" link renplacer} tool.
      With this you can rename file by pattern, or replace
      parts of filenames with something else.
      There is also a Find function.
    @{b}Sort@{ub}
      This will open/close/pop to front the @{"sort-window" link sort}.
      With this you can sort the list by a numerous of ways,
      automatically after using tools or manually.

    @{b}Open all tools@{ub}
      This will open all tool-windows.
    @{b}Close all tools@{ub}
      This will close all tool-windows.


  @{b}@{u}Visible columns@{uu}@{ub}

    @{b}Path@{ub}
      Show/hide the path column in the main lister.

    @{b}Old name@{ub}
      Show/hide the Old name column in the main lister.

    @{b}File Comment@{ub}
      Show/hide the File Comment column in the main lister.

    @{b}Filename length@{ub}
      Show/hide the filename length column in the main lister.


@endnode

@node prefs "MultiRen Preferences and Global settings"

 @{b}@{u}The MultiRen Preferences and Global settings window@{uu}@{ub}

  This is the preference window of MultiRen. It contains global
  settings that will be of relevance mostly for the tools, and others
  which will be used to decide what files is to be added according
  to the lenght of the filename and what is going to happen when
  you start MultiRen.

  It also contains a fix function which might come in handy if you
  happen to get two or more files with the same name, f.ex after
  using a tool.


  @{u}General@{uu}

    @{b}Show  Path,  Old name,  Comment,  Length@{ub}
      Which columns you want to be visible in the main lister.

    @{b}These are also letters@{ub}
      Characters entered here will not be treated as "special
      characters" when f.ex File Cleaner or Adaptor is looking
      for letters. Preferably this is where you can type in
      your locale letters for your country (if any).
      In sweden I would enter '' in this string. Note that
      your special letters has to have a upper and a lower
      case for this to work. Enter only the uppercase.

    @{b}Use New name as source for processing when using Tools@{ub}
      Set this if you want to use more than one tool to
      process your files without one tool canceling out
      the work done by another.

    @{b}Auto-setfilecommentswhenrenaming@{ub}
      With this switch enabled the file comments will be set to
      all @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled file in the list when you press @{b}Rename@{ub} in
      the @{"main window" link mainwin}. This way you don't have to open the
      @{"File Comment" link comment} and press @{b}Set Comments@{ub} there.

    @{b}Only close gadgets closes windows, menues doesn't@{ub}
      Enable this if you want the tool-windows to pop to front
      when selecting them from the menus if they are already
      opened instead of closing them.

    @{b}Skip annoying requesters and warnings@{ub}

      Setting this will prevent the following requesters
      from showing up:
      - The welcome requester
      - The requester that warns you when editing the
        @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} of a @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed file.
      - The warning when pressing the Rename or Undo rename
        buttons in the @{"main window" link mainwin}.
      - The requester asking you to update renamed file(s)
        after a rename.
      - The warning requester when updating renamed file(s).
      - The requester telling you that you have duplicates
        of some filenames. (The files are selected anyway.)
      - The requester telling you there were no dublicates
        to fix.
      - The requester asking you to clear the list before
        adding new files to it.
      - The requester warning you when clearing the list
        with @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged files in.
      - The requester asking you to verify the files in a
        list you loaded.
      - The requester telling you one or more files could
        not be found after verify. (The files are selected
        anyway.)

    @{b}Rename .info files automatically@{ub}
      If you set this then you don't have to add the icon-files (.info)
      to the list and rename them for every file that have an icon.
      MultiRen will do it for you. It will also warn you if you add
      .info files to the list with this switch on.

    @{b}Save extension-lists@{ub}
      The extensions in the @{"Extension Editor" link extension} is from v1.2 and on
      saved in ProgDir:Lists/MultiRen.ext (a textfile). If you never
      use these extensions you might want to unselect this checkmark.

    @{b}Save Renplacer stuff@{ub}
      With this enabled the Source and Target strings and the list
      of patterns in the Renplacer tool will be saved when you save
      the preferences. The pattern list is saved in a separate file
      located in ProgDir:Lists/.

    @{b}Save now@{ub}
      This button will save the extension lists and the Renplacer
      pattern list to their files in ProgDir:Lists/.


  @{u}Duplicates@{uu}

    @{b}Check for duplicates of filenames after using Tools@{ub}
      This will tell MultiRen to automatically check for
      duplicates of filenames in the main lister after a
      tool has done its work.

    @{b}Autofix duplicates@{ub}
      This is if you want MultiRen to automatically fix
      duplicates of filenames in a Windows->DOS kind of way.

      Example:
      You have 3 duplicates of the filename "Mysong.mp3".
      MultiRen would then fix them as:
      "Myso~1.mp3", "Myso~2.mp3" and "Myso~3.mp3".
      Note that this has nothing to do with 8+3 characters.
      It would work with f.ex: "My long songname.mpeg3"
      which would then become: "My long songna~1.mpeg3"
      and so on..

    @{b}Add ~N instead of overwrite the last 2 chars@{ub}
      This will prevent MultiRen from overwriting the last 2
      characters of a filename with the number but instead
      add it to the filename.

      Example:
      You got (as above) 3 duplicates of "Mysong.mp3".
      MultiRen would then fix them as:  "Mysong~1.mp3",
      "Mysong~2.mp3" and "Mysong~3.mp3".

    @{b}Check for duplicates@{ub}
      If you want to check for duplicates. All duplicate files
      will be selected in the list.

    @{b}Fix duplicates@{ub}
      If you want to perform the fix of duplicates now. Fixing
      duplicates mean to add or insert the ~N.

    @{b}Delete duplicates@{ub}
      If you want to delete all duplicates filenames, except one.


  @{u}Loading@{uu}

    @{fg shine}Load with filename length restrictions

      Filenames..@{fg text}

        @{b}All sizes@{ub}
          This will add all files that you select no regards to
          the length of the filename (in characters) of the files.

        @{b}Shorter than@{ub}
          This will only add files with names that are shorter
          than the given length of the upper slider to the right.
          Example:
          Slidervalue 31 will add filenames with length 30 and
          below.

        @{b}Longer than@{ub}
          This will only add files with names that are longer
          than the given length of the lower slider to the right.
          Example:
          Slidervalue 15 will add filenames with length 16 and
          greater.

        @{b}Between@{ub}
          This will only add files with name-lenghts that are
          between the given length of the sliders to the right.
          The upper slider should have a lower value and the
          lower slider should have a higher value.
          Example:
          If the upper slider was 20 and the below 30 all filenames
          with length from 20 to 30 characters will be added.

        @{b}Out of bound@{ub}
          This will only add files with names that are @{u}not@{uu}
          between the given length of the sliders to the right.
          The upper slider should have a lower value and the
          lower slider should have a higher value.
          Example:
          If the upper slider was 20 and the below 30 all filenames
          with length from 0 to 19 and from 31 and up (to 512)
          will be added.

      @{b}Disable files out of range now@{ub}
        This will mark all files that wouldn't be added with the
        current restrictions as @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isabled. However, filenames
        within the restrictions that are already @{fg fill}D@{fg text}isabled will
        not be marked @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled.

      @{b}Ask for lengths of filenames@{ub}
        This will give you some info about the shortest and the
        longest filename in the list.

    @{b}Insert files shuffled into the list when adding@{ub}
      If you have this switch on files will not be added at the
      bottom of the list but rather inserted at random positions.
      This is practical if you have a list with items in a specific
      order (f.ex previously shuffled) and now you want to add more
      files randomly without re-shuffling the whole list.

      This switch is meaningless if you have autosort enabled in
      the @{"Sort" link sort} tool.


  @{u}Open on startup..@{uu}
    In this page you can select which windows you prefer to be
    opened when you start MultiRen. You can also select if you
    want a filerequester for adding files should open automatically
    when you start MultiRen.


  @{u}More settings..@{uu}

    @{fg shine}Progress gauges@{fg text}

      @{b}Use@{ub}
        This is if you want progress gauges to be displayed when many
        files are processed.

      @{b}If more files than@{ub}
        Here you can select how many files there have to be in the list
        for the gauges to pop up. If you only have a few files in the
        list it usually takes longer to open and close the gauge-window
        than it takes to process the files.

      @{b}Refresh every@{ub}
        Here you can set how many files you want to be processed between
        updates of the gauges.

    @{fg shine}Plugin management@{fg text}

      @{b}Reload plugins@{ub}
        This will load or reload the plugins.

      @{b}Flush plugins@{ub}
        This will flush all loaded plugins from the plugin list.

      @{b}Substitute Gen@{ub}
        This will open the @{"Substitute list Generator" link subgen} that is used
        to make a substitute.list that some plugins use to replace
        unwanted characters returned by the plugins.

      @{b}Load plugins at startup@{ub}
        With this selected plugins will be loaded directly when you
        start MultiRen so that you don't have to flip to the Plugins
        page in the Renplacer to load them.

      @{b}Do not rename a file if a plugin fails@{ub}
        If you rename files and use the information that some plugin(s)
        return and the plugin fails to find the information then the
        filenames will be empty or part empty. With this selected those
        filenames will be left untouched if a plugin fails to give info.

      @{b}Do not display plugin error requester@{ub}
        Normally when one or more plugins reports error MultiRen will
        sum up all errors and display a requester at the end of the
        Rename process. This might be annoying if you always know that
        some plugins will fail because you have a wide mix of different
        files in the list. Select this checkmark to skip those requesters.

    @{fg shine}Main window things@{fg text}

      @{b}Path and Old name to string@{ub}
        Normally when you select a file in the main lister and press a
        column other than the New name of the File Comment column the
        last selected of New name or File Comment will be put into the
        stringgadget in the main window.
        However, sometimes you might want to get the Old name or the Path
        to the stringgadget too. That when this checkmark gets useful.
        You cannot however edit the Old name or the Path this way,
        only view them in the stringgadget.

      @{b}Bars between flags@{ub}
        This will just show or hide the vertical bars in the main lister
        that is between the flag-columns. A user requested this.

      @{b}Whener to keep marker in the main string@{ub}
        Here you can set where you want the marker to be in the string-
        gadget when you select a new file. In v1.3 of MultiRen it was
        always set on "Last position" and in the versions before that it
        was set at the end.


  @{b}Save@{ub}
    This will save all the global settings except for the
    listviews in the Extension Editor tool.

  @{b}Load@{ub}
    This will load the previously saved settings.

  @{b}Use@{ub}
    This will use your settings and close the prefs window.

  @{b}Cancel@{ub}
    This will reset your last settings and closes the prefs window.
    Note: This will reset all gadgets to the last used setting,
          not just gadgets in the Preferences window.


@endnode

@node sort "Sort"

 @{b}@{u}The Sort Tool@{uu}@{ub}

  This tool is only for sorting the list so that you more easily
  can find the filenames you are looking for.
  You can get it to automatically sort the list after the use of
  other tools or after adding new files.


  @{fg shine}Sort by..@{fg text}

    @{b}Enabled@{ub}  - This will sort the list and put all @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled
               files at the top. 
    @{b}Changed@{ub}  - This will sort the list and put all @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged
               files at the top.
    @{b}Renamed@{ub}  - This will sort the list and put all @{fg fill}R@{fg text}enamed
               files at the top.
    @{b}Failed@{ub}   - This will sort the list and put all @{fg fill}F@{fg text}ailed
               files at the top.
    @{b}Length@{ub}   - This will sort the list by the length of the filenames.
               If the checkmark "Use New name as source..." is
               enabled in @{"prefs" link prefs}, the length is take from the
               @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub}, otherwise from the @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub}.
    @{b}Shuffle@{ub}  - This will to the opposite to sort, it will shuffle
               the files and place them in a random order.
               This could be useful if you want to make a random
               playlist or something.
    @{b}Path@{ub}     - This will sort the list by the paths of the files.
    @{b}Old name@{ub} - This will sort the list by the @{b}@{u}Old name@{uu}@{ub}'s.
    @{b}New name@{ub} - This will sort the list by the @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub}'s.
    @{b}Comment@{ub}  - This will sort by filecomments.
    @{b}Date@{ub}     - Sort based on file date.
               If you have an old MultiRen file list saved you will
               need to select "menu->List->Verify if files exist" first
               to update the file dates for the files in the list.

  @{b}Left offset@{ub}
    Here you can set an offset if there is some characters you do not
    want in the beginning of the filename/filecomment/etc to be majorities
    while sorting.
    Example:
      You have two files;
       "Archive.lha"
       "Banana boat.mod"

      If you now set this offset to 1 it will not sort by the first
      letter but by the second and the file "Banana boat.mod" will
      end up before the file "Archive.lha" as 'a' comes before 'r'.

  @{b}Autosort by@{ub}
    If "Enable Autosort" is selected then this autosort will be
    done after every use of tools and after adding files.

  @{b}Sort secondly by@{ub}
    If you sort by f.ex @{fg fill}C@{fg text}hanged then there are
    probably many changed files so if two changed files are to be
    sorted then MultiRen will sort on the entry selected here instead.

  @{b}Enable Autosort@{ub}
    This will enable the autosort mentioned above.

  @{b}Reverse sorting@{ub}
    This will make all sorting go backwards.
    F.ex "z" will be first and "a" last.

  @{b}Case sensitive@{ub}
    This will make all sorting case sensitive.
    Uppercase will come first.

  @{b}Sort by extension@{ub}
    With this enabled the sorting will be based on just the extension
    and not the whole filename. Files without extension will be first
    in the list. If you have set an offset it will be applied so that
    offset 0 is at the point and offset 1 at the first character in the
    actual extension.
    Extension will be searched for for Path, Old name, New name and Comment.

  @{b}Number aware sort@{ub}
    If you select this, the filename "2 - test" will come before
    "10 - test". Without number aware sort, MultiRen will sort by
    characters and therefore only see that '1' comes before '2' and
    then put number 10 before number 2. This function prevents this
    wrong behaviour.

  @{b}Unsort@{ub}
    This will undo a preview sort action.
    The Unsort is canceled everytime you add files.

  @{b}Close@{ub}
    This will close this window.

  @{i}<popup button> @{ui}
    If you press this button the sort window will shrink down a bit.
    Another popup button will appear to the right in the smaller window
    then which you can press to get back the original size.


@endnode

@node filecleaner "File Cleaner"

 @{b}@{u}The File Cleaner Tool@{uu}@{ub}

  This tool is for cleaning up filenames from unwanted characters
  and maybe changing the cAsE of the letters to make the names
  look nicer and more readable.


  @{u}What to clean@{uu}

    @{b}Do with s p a c e s@{ub}
      Select what you want File Cleaner to do when encounter spaces
      character. There are two kinds of these characters in most fonts.
      Space is the normal " " which is quite short. There is however
      another "Ā", a white space, which is a bit longer in high-quality
      fonts. It can be prettier to use the white space instead of a
      normal space in some places.

    @{b}Do with white spaces@{ub}
      This option lets you change or remove those special ASCII-160
      white space "Ā" characters described above.

    @{b}Do with _underscore_@{ub}
      Select what you want File Cleaner to do when encounter underscores.

    @{b}Do with commas ,,,@{ub}
      Select what you want File Cleaner to do when encounter a comma
      character.

    @{b}Do with points ...@{ub}
      Select what you want File Cleaner to do when encounter a period
      character.

    @{b}Do with hyphens -@{ub}
      Select what you want File Cleaner to do when encounter a hyphen
      character. There are two kinds of these characters in most fonts.
      Hyphen is the normal "-" which is quite short. There is however
      another "Ł", a dash, which is a bit longer in some high-quality
      fonts. It can be prettier to use the dash instead of a hyphen in
      some places.

    @{b}Do with dashes Ł@{ub}
      This option lets you change or remove those special ASCII-173
      dashes "Ł" characters described above.

    @{b}Do with letters aBc@{ub}
      Select what you want File Cleaner to do when encounter letters.
      This also includes letter in the string "Theese are also letters"
      under @{"prefs" link prefs}.
      @{fg shine}Nothing@{fg text}   - Nothing will happen to letters.
      @{fg shine}UPPERCASE@{fg text} - All letters will be converted to uppercase.
      @{fg shine}lowercase@{fg text} - All letters will be converted to lowercase.
      @{fg shine}First Letter Upper@{fg text}    - The first letter in every word will be
                              converted to UPPERcase, all the following
                              characters will be converted to lowercase.
      @{fg shine}Initial letter upper@{fg text}  - This will do about the same as the above
                              but only the first letter in every sentance
                              of the filename will be converted to uppercase
                              while the others will be converted to lowercase.
                              A sentence is started after a period (".") or
                              parntheses ("()[]{}") or a dash surrounded b y
                              spaces (" - ").
      @{fg shine}fIRST lETTER lOWER@{fg text}    - This will do the inverse of what
                              "First Letter Upper" does.
      @{fg shine}Invert case@{fg text}           - F.ex "FileName.MOD" will be "fILEnAME.mod".

    @{b}Do with numbers 123@{ub}
      Select what you want File Cleaner to do when encounter numbers
      0-9.
      @{fg shine}Nothing@{fg text}               - Nothing will happen to any number character.
      @{fg shine}Remove@{fg text}                - Remove any number character encountered
                               in the filename.
      @{fg shine}Remove leading zeroes@{fg text} - This will remove all zeroes that preceeds
                               a number (1-9). If there are only zeroes in
                               a row, they will be reduced to just one "0".
                               Example:
                                "Img0001.jpg"  will be  "Img1.jpg"
                                "Test00"  will be  "Test0".

  @{u}Advanced..@{uu}

    @{b}Do not process file extensions@{ub}
      This will prevent File Cleaner from doing any "cleaning" on extensions.
      Note that the way extensions is recognized has nothing to do with the
      settings in the Extension Editor tool.

    @{b}Do not lower loNely uppercase@{ub}
      This is if you are using "First Letter Upper" on filenames that looks
      like this f.ex: "My SongName.mp3", or maybe "Artist - LetItBe.mp2" and
      don't want them to become "My Songname.mp2" and "Artist - Letitbe.mp2".
      It then preserves uppercase characters that is in the middle of a
      filename and is not "supposed" to be in lowercase.

    @{b}Reduce duplicates of characters@{ub}

     This is for reducing multiples of characters in a row to just one
     of the same char in the filename.
     Example:
      Contents in the string gadget: "e-"

      Pressing Clean up would now (among the other actions) change a
      filename as this:
      "File---namee.txt"  would be  "File-name.txt"

     This action will be taken @{u}before@{uu} any other action in File Cleaner!

      @{b}Disable this function@{ub}
        This will disable this function.
        Better than having to clear the string gadget to disable it...


    @{b}Other characters to act on..@{ub}
      Do with chars in the string: Here you select what to do when File Cleaner
                                   encounter one of the characters in the
                                   string below this cycle gadget in the GUI.

  @{b}Clean up@{ub}
    Press this when you have got all your settings as you want them.
    The cleaning will then begin.

  @{b}Close@{ub}
    Close the File Cleaner window.


@endnode

@node adaptor "Adaptor"

 @{b}@{u}The Adaptor Tool@{uu}@{ub}

  This tool is for adapting the lenght of your filenames to a for
  you more suitable length. This is done in a way that is supposed
  to preserve as much information in the name as possible and only
  remove less important characters.
  You can choose if you only want to short down the length of filenames
  that are too long or prolong names that are "to short".


  @{u}How to adapt@{uu}

    @{b}Try to adapt filename length to the following length@{ub}
      Set this slider to the length you want your new filenames to be in.
      Note that the filenames might not become the exact length you set
      if you do not activate the checkmark "Always adapt exact..."
      below. This might be because Adaptor thing the filename would look
      pathetic unless another (or a few more) characters are removed.

    @{fg shine}Adapt names that are..@{fg text}

      @{b}Too long@{ub}
        All filenames in the main list will be cut down to the length
        specified by the slider above if not already short enough.
        (See adaption for info about how this is done.)

      @{b}Too short@{ub}
        All filenames in the main list will be made longer or up to
        the length specified by the slider above if not already long
        enough.
        (See adaption for info about how this is done.)

      @{b}Adapt both@{ub}
        This would be the same as selecting both of the above.

    @{b}Always adapt exact to the given size@{ub}
      This will force Adaptor to change the filenames to the exact lenght
      given by the slider. Don't use this unless you have a special
      reason as the filenames might end up looking a bit pathetic.
      Ex.
      You got a filename: "[Artist] - FileName.mod" and want to short
      it down 3 characters to 20 chars. The result might then be:
      "Artist]-FileName.mod" which is not so good. If the checkmark is
      not selected, the "]" would also be gone and it would look more nice!

  @{u}Advanced..@{uu}

    @{fg shine}Settings for names that is to be shorter@{fg text}

      @{b}Cut filenames. Ignore other settings.@{ub}
        This will make the Adaptor to cut down the filenames to the
        specified lenght instead of "compressing" the name.
        Ex: "File Name.ext" would be "File Na.ext" if cut down to 11
        characters.

      @{b}Be aware of extensions when cutting@{ub}
        With this switch, some "intelligence" will also be put into
        the cutter so that it will only cut down the filename and
        not the extension with it.

      @{b}Never remove any letters@{ub}
        This will forbid the Adaptor to remove any letters, including
        those extra letters specified in the prefs, when shorting
        down filenames. This switch will however be ignored when
        you use the "Cut filenames" switch.

      @{b}Do not remove theese characters@{ub}
        Here you can enter characters you do not want to be removed.
        If you enter here f.ex !# the characters ! and # will not be
        removed when shorting down names even if adaptor would want
        that. This switch will however be ignored when you use the
        "Cut filenames" switch.

    @{fg shine}Settings for names that is to be longer@{fg text}

      @{b}Character to use as lengthener@{ub}
        The character selected here will be the one that Adaptor uses
        when a "blank" character is to be inserted in a filename.

      @{b}Do not separate lonely numbers@{ub}
        This will prevent Adaptor from inserting "blank" characters
        between a single number character and another character.
        Example:
        You have "Song_no1.mod". With this checkmark selected it will
        not become "Song_no_1.mod" but stay as it was. But if you got
        "Song_no15.mod" it @{i}will@{ui} become "Song_no_15.mod" anyway.

  @{b}Adapt@{ub}
    Pressing this will perform the adaption of the filenames in the main list.

  @{b}Close@{ub}
    This closes the window.


@endnode

@node extension "Extension Editor"

 @{b}@{u}The Extension Editor Tool@{uu}@{ub}

  This tool is for managing filenames' extensions.
  It can add, remove, change or fix extension in a few different
  ways. Most of the things this tool can do is also possible to
  do manually with the @{"Renplacer" link renplacer} tool but that is ofcource
  alittle more work than using this tool :)

  For example, changing all your modules from "mod.songname" to
  "songname.mod" can be done with only two mouseclicks.
  Or changing all "picture.jpg" to "picture.jpeg" can also be
  done with two mouseclicks.

  The extension Editor works in essentially 3 different modes:

    1.  You have selected an extension in the list of extensions.
      If you have done this then only filenames which have an extension
      that matches this selected extension in this list will be affected.
      Note that it matters what column you click in when selecting an
      extension (except for @{b}Change@{ub})!

    2.  No item is selected in the list of extensions but the list is
        not ghosted. You can press the @{b}Off@{ub} button to do this.
      If this is the case then all filenames which have an extension
      that matches @{i}any @{ui}of the items in the left column of the
      list will be affected by an operation.

    3.  You have selected the checkmark "Ignore list, work general" and
        the list of extensions and its managing buttons has been ghosted.
      If this is the can you can not use @{b}Append@{ub} (because nothing is
      selected to be appended) or @{b}Change@{ub} (because no pair of extensions
      can be selected for change).
      In this mode actions will be takes on all filenames which have any
      extension, but nothing will happen to files without an extension.

    Ofcourse actions will only be taken on @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled files.


  @{fg shine}Extension@{fg text}

    @{b}Add@{ub}: This will add an entry in the list of extensions.
         Use the string field below to type in a new extension.
         In the left column you have to place a point (.) on that
         side of the extension it would have a point if it was in a
         filename.
         Ex. Enter ".jpg" and if you want to affect files named
         "picname.jpg". Files looking like this "jpg.picname" will
         not be recognized.
    @{b}Rem@{ub}: This will remove the selected pair of extension from the
         list.
    @{b}Clr@{ub}: This will remove all extension from the list and
         automatically select "Ignore list, work general".
    @{b}Off@{ub}: This will unselect the active item in the list and
         thus make you able to apply actions on all extensions in the
         list at the same time. Note that only extensions in the left
         column will be matched agains.
    @{b}Def@{ub}: This will add the default extensions to the list. Useful if
         you accidently would press Clr.

    @{b}<string>@{ub}
      In this string gadget you can edit the selected extension in
      the list.

    @{b}Fix extension as..@{ub}
      This will apply changes to the filenames whos extensions have a
      match. One of the three modes described above will apply.

      @{fg shine}lowercase@{fg text}:          Convert the extension(s) to lowercase.
      @{fg shine}UPPERCASE@{fg text}:          Convert the extension(s) to uppercase.
      @{fg shine}First letter upper@{fg text}: Set the first letter in the extension(s)
                          to uppercase and the rest to lowercase.

    @{b}Ignore list, work general@{ub}
      If this is selected the list will be completely ignored and
      Extension Editor will scan for something that looks like
      extensions instead, the same way @{"Adaptor" link adaptor} and @{"File Cleaner" link filecleaner} does.

    @{b}Select all matching@{ub}
      This action will select matching extensions, according to the
      three modes described above, in the main lister. In mode 3 f.ex.
      all files that have an extension will be selected.

  @{b}Remove@{ub}
    Any matching extension, according to the modes, will be removed.

  @{b}Append@{ub}
    This requires that an extension is selected in the list of extension.
    All files which doesn't have an extension will get this selected
    extension appended to itself.

  @{b}Make filename.ext@{ub}
    This will convert all filenames which have a matching extension
    at the beginning of the filename to be moved to the end of the
    filename. Ex. "mod.songname" will become "songname.mod".

  @{b}Make ext.filename@{ub}
    This will do exactly the opposite of what @{b}Make filename.ext@{ub} does.

  @{b}Change@{ub}
    This requires that a pair of extensions is selected in the list of
    extension. All filenames which have an extension matching the selected
    extension in the left column will be changed to the extension in the
    right column.

  @{b}Close@{ub}
    This closes the window.


@endnode

@node renplacer "Renplacer"

 @{b}@{u}The Renplacer Tool@{uu}@{ub}

  This tool is used for advanced pattern Renaming and Replacing,
  hense the name Renplacer :)
  It however also have got a nice Find function which also can use
  uses pattern. See examples for the three methods below.

  This is also the window where you can use the @{"plugins" link renplacer 200} if you
  have installed any. The plugins returns specified strings that
  you can use by inserting wildcard with indexes matching the
  plugin-strings you want to use.
  Read more further down under @{fg text}Plugins@{fh text} on this page.

  This applies for all that are using wildcards:
  * represent zero to @{i}n @{ui}number of unknown characters.
  ? represents exactly one unknown character.

  The rename function uses a kind of special way when parsing
  wildcards when more than one is used. It requires that every
  wildcard has it's own ID character, index, following the asterix
  (* or ?) itself. See the examples.
  ID and index is exactly the same thing when mentioned further
  down the text.

  If you have a * somewhere in Source and just a matching (= with the
  same index) ? in Target, only the first character in the string
  represented by the * will be inserted where the ? is placed.

  Example of a rename in simple mode (one wildcard in Source = no indexes):
   Filename: "A little test.iff"
   Source:   "* test.iff"
   Target:   "? test.iff"
   The resulting filename would be "A test.iff".

  One little detail that the Renplacer can not do is the ability to match
  against non-existing parts of filenames.
  Example: "Test.~(mp1|mp2)"
  This would then search for, or rename files that do @{b}not@{ub} end with
  mp1 or mp2. However, this is not possible (yet).

  @{fg shine}Rename/Replace/Find@{fg text}

    @{b}Source@{ub}
      If you want to rename, then enter a filename pattern here. It may
      contain * and ? which will be treated as wildcards.

      If you want to replace then enter a part of a filename which you
      want to replace. * and ? is @{b}not@{ub} used as wildcards when replacing
      but treated as any other character.

      If you want to find one or more filenames then enter a pattern
      to search for. Remember not to use indexed wildcards when you use
      Find, even if you use more than one wildcard.

    @{b}Target@{ub}
      If you are renaming, you enter here your target filename, possibly
      containing one or more of your wildcards. Enter them @{u}with@{uu} ID if
      you are using ID in Source.

      For replace, just enter the thing you want Source to be replaced by,
      possibly nothing.

      Target is not used when Finding.

    @{b}Store
    Remove@{ub}
      These two buttons are used to store or remove a Source/Target set
      to or from the Renplacer pattern cache. You can get a stored pattern
      by clicking on the popdown button at the right of these buttons and
      then select one of your stored patterns.

      This feature is very nice if you often use more than one pattern
      and don't want to retype them all the time.

      If the "Save memo lists" is set in the prefs then these memos will
      be saved immediately when you use Store or Remove.

    @{b}Sort@{ub}
      With this button you can sort the memo list. The following settings
      from the @{"Sort" link sort} tool applies:
        Reverse sorting
        Case sensitive
        Number aware sort

    @{b}Parse strings case insensitive@{ub}
      With this selected the source will be compared against filenames
      with no regards to the cAsE of a filename.
      Example:
       If you enter "filename" in source, RenPlacer will also act on a
       file called "FILENAME" or "fILeNAme".

    @{i}<Single/Index> @{ui}
      This text-field tells you wether you are in Indexed wildcard mode
      or no-index wildcard mode for Rename. Normally index will be used
      if you enter more than one wildcard (* or ?) in Source, else no
      indexes will be used. Exception is when plugins is activated, then
      index is always used!

    @{b}Rename@{ub}
      This will rename all files matching Source as Target.
      This can be done in 2 different ways, Simple and Advanced.

      The simple way is automatically used when only one wildcard is
      used; one * or one ?.

      Examples of using the Simple method (no index):

        Main list contains (among others):
         "CarPicture1.gif"
         "CarPicture2.gif"
         "Cardassian speach.mp2"
         "Cartoon"
         ....

        Source: "Car*"
        Target: "Test*hello?"

        Result in main list:
         "TestPicture1.gifhelloP"
         "TestPicture2.gifhelloP"
         "Testdassian speach.mp2hellod"
         "Testtoonhellot"

        Give this a thought and try it out.

      The advanced way is chosen when multiple wildcards are used.
      Every wildcard must then have a unique ID character.
      Ex: Source: "File*1name?2.*3" where I choosed 1,2 and 3 as my
      unique characters. The power with this technique is that you
      then can use the same ID'd wildcards in the Target string
      how many times you want (incl. not at all) and in any order
      you want!

      Examples of using the Advanced method (with index):

       Main list contains (among others):
        "[Album A] - {Artist A},The first song.mp3"
        "[Album A]-{Artist B},The second song.mp3"
        "[Album A] - {Artist B},The third song.mp3"
        .....

       Let's now say that you want the artist to be where album is and
       at the same time get rid of the album, the {} and the comma.
       Then enter this:

       Source: "[*a]*1-*2{*b},*c"       (I use a, b, c, 1 and 2 as ID-chars)
       Target: "[*b] - *c"

       Result in main list:
         "[Artist A] - The first song.mp3"
         "[Artist B] - The second song.mp3"
         "[Artist B] - The third song.mp3"
         .....

       Give it a good thought and try some experiments. Remember that
       you always has the possibility to "Restore Changed file(s)" from the
       @{"main window menu" link mainmenu} or restore one file at a time by pressing
       Restore in the @{"main window" link mainwin}.

    @{b}Replace@{ub}
      This is a function that is much simpler than Rename. It does not
      make use of any wildcards.

      Example:
      Main list contains (among others):
        "The first song.mp3"
        "The second song.mp3"
        "The third song.mp3"
        .....

      To change the word "song" to "melody" in every filename you
      just enter this:

      Source: "song"
      Target: "melody"

      Result in main list:
        "The first melody.mp3"
        "The second melody.mp3"
        "The third melody.mp3"
        .....

      Or if you want to remove "The" from every filename then enter
      this:

      Source: "The "
      Target: ""

      Result in main list:
        "first song.mp3"
        "second song.mp3"
        "third song.mp3"
        .....

    @{b}Find@{ub}
      This is used to find a particular filename or multiple ones
      using wildcards. All files that is "found" will be selected
      in the main lister so that you then can do what you like with
      them. (Suggested is to choose "Enable only.. selected file(s)"
      in the @{"main window menu" link mainmenu} and then sort by Enabled after you have
      used Find. This way you can much easier get control over the
      files you found.)

      Example of three files and a pattern to find them.

      Main list contains (among others):
        "Arvid1 - My song.mp3"
        "Arvid2 - Something else.mp3"
        "Arvid3 - A third tune.mp3"
        ...

      Source: "Arvid? - *.mp3"

      The three files above should now have been selected.

    @{b}Close@{ub}
      This closes the window.


  @{fg shine}Plugins@{fg text}

   @{u}How to use plugins:@{uu}
    Plugins will never rename any files. Plugins will just provide you
    with one or more strings that you can use to compose you filenames
    anyway you want. You access the strings as standard indexed wildcards!

   Example:
    Let's say we have a plugin that can extract the artist and the
    songname out of MP3-files. And let's say that the artist has the
    index `A' and the songname has the index `B' and we write:

    Source: "*1.mp3"
    Target: "[*A] - *B.mp3"

    The result could now be: "[Ace of Base] - Beautiful Life.mp3"
    The old filename, *1, is discarded in this example, but you could
    of course also include *1 in the Target aswell.

    Nice, don't you think?? :-)


     Here is also a link to the @{"Developer guide" link Developers/MultiRen-Plugins.guide/main}.

    @{b}<the lister>@{ub}
      This lister will contain all plugins that were loaded correctly
      by MultiRen.
      It has 7 columns:
       @{b}@{u}Use@{ub}@{uu} -> If you want to use this string.
        This can have the values Yes or No which will control if you
        want to use this plugin or not. Useful to set to No if you want
        to use this plugins' index for something else. You must set it
        to Yes if you want to use it, otherwise it will not be executed
        when you press Rename.

       @{b}@{u}Index@{ub}@{uu} -> The index this string will get.
        This is the ID character that this string will be substituted
        with. NOTE: It is possible to give multiple strings the same
        index but only the one first in the list with that index will
        then be used! Practical if you want to test different plugins
        without the need to change index or changing the Target string
        every time.

       @{b}@{u}Name@{ub}@{uu} -> Which filename to send to the plugin.
        Here you can set if you want to send the Old name or the New name
        to the plugin in question. Typically you would set it to Old name
        if the plugin extract data from the file, and set it to New name
        if the plugin manipulates the filename only. The plugins themselves
        choose default values here.

       @{b}@{u}Returned string@{ub}@{uu} -> Info of what you will get if you use this string.
        This shows information about what you will get if you use this
        string.

       @{b}@{u}Plugin@{ub}@{uu} -> The name of the plugin.
        This is the name of the plugin that provides the string. One
        plugin can provide many strings and then you will see "---"
        for the rest of the strings that this plugin provides.

       @{b}@{u}C@{ub}@{uu} -> Configuration of the plugin.
        If you press this, a configuration window (or something) might
        popup that lets you configure the plugin. All plugins may not
        support configuration.

       @{b}@{u}I@{ub}@{uu} -> Information about the plugin.
        If you press this, the plugin will hopefully put up an about-
        requester or something telling it's version and so. All plugins
        should support this.

   @{b}Index:@{ub}
     Here you can change the index for the current plugin.

   @{b}Use plugins@{ub}
     Switching this off is like setting all plugins to Use=No.
     Note: When renaming using plugins, index is @{i}always @{ui}used, even
     if you only use one wildcard, from plugins or from Source!


  Note: If you suspect that a plugin hanged or crashed you can send Ctrl-C
        to MultiRen to keep it from waiting for that plugin forever.


@endnode

@node numberer "Numberer"

 @{b}@{u}The Numberer Tool@{uu}@{ub}

  This tool is for making fileseries in a very simple, yet flexible way.
  You have alot of different numberingsystems to choose from; Binary,
  Decimal, Hexadecimal and Alfa.

  To make all files have the same name before the numbering is done,
  use the @{"Renplacer" link renplacer} tool. It is namely so that Numberer doesn't
  care if the files have different names, it just numbers all
  @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled files from the top of the list and down.

  For example, if you got a bounch of iff files with different names
  that you want numbered in s strict way:
  Open the @{"Renplacer" link renplacer} tool.
  Enter in Source: *
  Enter in Target: MyFiles.iff
  Press "Rename". You now might get a warning about duplicates of
  filenames, ignore that. Open this Numberer tool and just fix the
  numbering as you like and press "Add numberserie".


  @{b}Example of the first filename@{ub}
    This is just an example of how the first filename in a serie
    would look like.

  @{b}Numbersystem@{ub}
    Here you can choose what kind of numbersystem you want to use
    for your serie.
    The systems uses the following chars:
      Binary (well known): 0-1 (Just ones and zeroes, base 2)
      Decimal (standard) : 0-9 (The standard countingsystem we
                                are used to, base 10)
      Hexadecimal (known from computers): 0-9,A-F (base 16)
      Alfa (my invention): A-Z (Works as a normal numbersystem but
                                uses the letters A to Z instead of
                                numbers, base 26 (there are 26 letters)

  @{b}Hex/Alfa case@{ub}
    Here you select if you want the letters in the Hexadecimal and
    Alfa number system to use upper or lower case.

  @{b}Put numbers at@{ub}
    This is where in the filename you want the numbers to be put.
    The the example above.
    If an extension is not found when adding to the beginning of
    the extension, the number will become the extension.
    When adding to the end of the extension and an extension is
    not found, the number will just be added to the end of the
    filename.

  @{b}Start at number@{ub}
    This is the number of which the numbering would start.
    If you f.ex write '5', the numbers would be 5,6,7,8... etc.
    This string accepts all numbersystems (bin/dec/hex/alfa)
    but to be able to use another system than decimal, in this
    string, you have to put a prefix ahead of the number.
    The prefixes are:
      @{b}%@{ub} for binary.      Ex: %100101 base-2 (37 in decimal)
      @{b}$@{ub} for hexadecimal. Ex: $4E base-16 (78 in decimal)
      @{b}@@@{ub} for alfa.        Ex: @RB base-26 (443 in decimal)

    You can not use negativ numbers. The count will always increment
    by one. If you want descending numbers you have two choises:
    1. If you have sorted your list then toggle "Reverse sorting"
       and sort again, then apply the number serie.
    2. If you have not sorted your list then set "Reverse sorting"
       and press Unsort (yes, Unsort :)), then apply your number
       serie.

  @{b}Separator@{ub}
    Enter a character here, or pick one from the popdown menu,
    that is to be used as a separator between the number and the
    part of the filename where the number would be.

  @{b}Change@{ub}
    Use this to change to another separator character for already
    numbered files without having to re-number them. Just select a
    new separator char and press Change.

  @{b}Add@{ub}
    Use this to add a separator character between the filename and
    the number for files with a number serie which is not separated
    from the filename. Select a separator char and press Add.

  @{b}Min # of digits@{ub}
    This is the shortest number of characters that the number will
    have. However, you can not set a maximum number of chars, that
    is decided from how big the number itself is.
    Example:
     If you set this to 2, the numbering would start as 00, 01, 02...
     10, 11, 12... and then continue like this; 99, 100, 101, 102...

  @{b}Fix@{ub}
    This is if you want to change the minimum number of digits of
    an already applied number serie.

    Useful if you f.ex. have filenames like:
      "File_1.jpg", "File_2.jpg" ... "File_10.jpg", "File_11.jpg" etc.
    But you would like:
      "File_01.jpg", "File_02.jpg" ... "File_10.jpg", "File_11.jpg" etc.

  @{b}Add numberserie@{ub}
    Press this to apply your numberserie to your @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled filenames.
    Not that if you already has a numberserie on your files, it
    will not automatically be removed before the new numbers is
    applied.

  @{b}Remove existing numberserie@{ub}
    With this button you can remove an existing numberserie.
    However, this function is not very general but requires that
    you set most settings so that they matches the numberserie
    you want to remove.

    To make the removal as perfect as possible you need to set the
    following gadgets to reflect the numberserie:
      Numbersystem, Hex/Alfa case, Put numbers at, Separator or
      Min # of digits, If you use a separator character you don't
      need to set "Min # of digits".

    To make a more general removal:
      Set "Numbersystem" to hexadecimal.
      Set "Hex/Alfa case" to the right case (if you have a numbersystem
      with letters).
      Set "Put numbers at" to the position where the number is.
      Set "Separator" to the character used, and if no separator is
      used, set "Min # of digits" to 1.

    It's always a problem to remove Alfa-numbered filenames as it might
    remove the whole filename if no separator is used or if you use the
    Remove-button the wrong way..!

  @{b}Close@{ub}
    This closes the window.


@endnode

@node comment "File Comment"

 @{b}@{u}The File Comment Tool@{uu}@{ub}

  This tool is for managing the filecomments of your files.

  You can manually change every filecomment or you can customize
  them automatically to get time/date, filelength, filename and
  such in them.

  There is however not a direct way to use the extension tools
  on your comments, but to get around this problem you can
  temporary swap the @{b}@{u}New name@{uu}@{ub} and the comments
  and then, having your comments as filenames, alter them with
  the tools and finally swap back.


  @{b}From@{ub}
    The source for the operation you want to perform.
    If you select Custom the string gadget below will be
    active and you can enter a (formatted) string that will
    be set to your target.

  @{b}To@{ub}
    This is the target of the operation. This is be set to
    either New name of File Comment.

  @{b}Custom@{ub}
    In this string you can enter a (formatted) string to be used
    as a template for the file comments.
    Select formatting switches from the popdown menu to the right.

    The switches are as follows:
     %o - Will insert the current Old name
     %n - Will insert the current New name
     %p - Will insert the current path ending with ":" or "/"
     %c - Will insert the current comment
     %e - Will insert the extension of the New name
     %E - Will insert the extension of the Old name
     %O - Will insert the current Old name without its extension
     %N - Will insert the current New name without its extension
     %lf - Will give the file length of the current file in bytes
     %lF - Will give the file length in bytes with thousand separators
     %lk - Will give the file length of the current file in kilobytes
     %lK - Will give the file length in kilobytes with thousand separators
     %lm - Will give the file length of the current file in megabytes
     %lo - Will give the current Old name length
     %ln - Will give the current New name length
     %ly - Will give the current year as a 4-digit number
     %lp - Will give the last directory in the path without ":" or "/"
     %s - Will give the current second in two digits
     %m - Will give the current minute in two digits
     %h - Will give the current hour in tw digits
     %w - Will give the current week day. Ex. Monday
     %D - Will give the current day of the month
     %M - Will give the current month as a number
     %Y - Will give the current year as a 2-digit number
     %fs - Will give the filedates second in two digits
     %fm - Will give the filedates minute in two digits
     %fh - Will give the filedates hour in tw digits
     %fw - Will give the filedates week day. Ex. Monday
     %fD - Will give the filedates day of the month
     %fM - Will give the filedates month as a number
     %fY - Will give the filedates year as a 2-digit number
     %% - Will safely insert a %-char
     %[ - Will safely insert a [-char
     %] - Will safely insert a ]-char
     %t - Will insert a tab-stop making all %t's be placed exactly beneath
          each other. You can have any number of %t's in a string.
     %\\ - Linefeed. This is not supported for file comments, only for text export.

    After every switch (except %%, %[, %] and %\) you can write
    [<offset>;<length>] so that you may pick just a part of a filename
    or anything when you are composing your filecomments. If <length> is
    omitted then the string will be read to the end. If <length> is
    negative it will read to the end minus the number you wrote as a
    negative number. %o[17,-4] would mean to start to read at the 17th
    character in the Old name and read until the end but not including
    the last 4 characters.

    Example:
      Let's say that we have an Old name that looks like this:
        @{fg shine}My vacation 03 - Swimming.jpg@{fg text}.

      Then we could write..:
        @{fg shine}%o[17,-4], Pic no.%o[12,2] - %[Date: %D/%M-%ly%]@{fg text}

      ...and get a result something like this:
        @{fg shine}Swimming, Pic no.03 - [Date: 14/6-2001]@{fg text}

    Example using the %t in two places:
      Let's say we have four filenames which have different sizes:

        @{fg shine}ID3-Tag.mrp@{fg text}
        @{fg shine}QuotedPrintable.mrp@{fg text}
        @{fg shine}QuotedPrintable.readme@{fg text}
        @{fg shine}Substitute.list@{fg text}

      Then we could write:
        @{fg shine}%o%t - (%lF) %t:Draft from plugins directory@{fg text}

      ..and get:

        @{fg shine}ID3-Tag.mrp            - (7.672) :Draft from plugins directory@{fg text}
        @{fg shine}QuotedPrintable.mrp    - (3.052) :Draft from plugins directory@{fg text}
        @{fg shine}QuotedPrintable.readme - (981)   :Draft from plugins directory@{fg text}
        @{fg shine}Substitute.list        - (29)    :Draft from plugins directory@{fg text}

      ..in very nice columns.


  @{b}Store  Remove@{ub}
    These two buttons is used to store or remove custom strings to or
    from the memo list for the File Comment tool. You can get a stored
    string by clicking on the popdown button at the right of these
    buttons and then select one of your stored strings.

    This feature is very nice if you often use more than one custom
    string and don't want to retype it all the time.

    If the "Save memo lists" is set in the prefs this will be saved
    immediately when you use Store or Remove.

  @{b}Use two digits for date@{ub}
    With this set, the day (%D) and month (%M) will always be
    printed as a 2-digit number.
    I would make sense to unselect this if you want to show a
    date as; 3/7 instead of 03/07.
    The year is always 2 (or 4) digits.

  @{b}Set From -> To@{ub}
    This will copy the thing select in the "From"-cycle to the
    "To"-field. If custom is selected, the Custom-string will
    be parsed and copied to the filecomments.

  @{b}Swap New name/Comment@{ub}
    This will swap the New name and the filecomment no matter
    what "From" and "To" is set on. (This is changed from earlier
    versions..)
    You can use this if you want to use the tools on your
    filecomments as they doesn't work directly in the comment-
    field, then swap back.

  @{b}Set Comment@{ub}
    This will set the comments in the list to your files on
    disk.
    @{u}Attention:@{uu} You cannot get back you original filecomments
    after you have pressed this button!  Therefor, save the list
    with your original filecomments first in case you want your
    old ones back later. When you're finished, you just swap back.

  @{b}Get Comment@{ub}
    This will re-read the filecomments from the files. Sort of like
    an undo function.

  @{b}Clear comments@{ub}
    This will delete all comment on your @{fg fill}E@{fg text}nabled files in the
    list.

  @{b}Close@{ub}
    This closes the window.


@endnode

@node subgen "The Substitute List Generator"

 @{b}@{u}The Substitute List Generator@{uu}@{ub}

  There is now integrated into MultiRen and called simply
  the Substitute Generator.

  This program makes a little list of replacement characters that
  some plugins use to filter the result they send to MultiRen with.

  As an example; ?*#():/ is not really allowed in AmigaDOS filenames
  and they are therefor already defined in the substitute.list that
  comes with MultiRen. Now you maybe see the point of this thing :)

  @{u}Usage:@{uu}

    @{b}Replace this:@{ub}
      Here you enter a character that you want to replace.

    @{b}with this:@{ub}
      Here you enter a character to replace the other character with.
      This can also be empty and then the other character will be
      removed instead of replaced.

    @{b}Use the substitute list@{ub}
      This is if you generally want the plugins to use this substitute
      list. Some plugins might have their own setting here and only use
      this value as default.
      You probably want to use this when changing file names with plugins
      but you wouldn't need this when editing file comment.

    @{b}Add@{ub}
      After you have filled in the two stringgadgets above you press
      this to get the new entry into the list. You cannot press Add
      if the first string is empty!

    @{b}Change@{ub}
      If you want to edit an entry you first activate it in the list,
      then edit the stringgadgets, then press this button.

    @{b}Remove@{ub}
      Removes the selected entry from the list.

    @{b}Clear@{ub}
      This will without warning clear the whole list.

    @{b}Cancel@{ub}
      This exits the program and forgets about any changes.

    @{b}Ok@{ub}
      This saves the list and closes the window. You must reload
      the list in every plugin now to make them use the new list.
      Some plugins have a reload feature, otherwise you have to
      press "Reload plugins" in the prefs of MultiRen to get the
      new list into the plugins.


@endnode

@node History "History"

  @{fg shine}@{b}What's new and what MultiRen already features!
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Made it possible to sort by date.

   @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Added possibility to show date in the list.

   @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Fixed garbage being inserted as date in File Comment tool
           when a file didn't exists.

   @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Some spelling.

  @{fg shine}v1.69
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}**@{fg text} Fixed drag'n'drop of directories in Ambient. Ambient reports
      dropped drawers in a different (albeit more logical) way
      than WB.

   @{fg fill}**@{fg text} Added some stack.. AGAIN, since the NListview.mcp seems more
      stack hungry than ever.

   @{fg fill}**@{fg text} The MUI preferences now only list the external classes actually
      used by MultiRen, unless you have an older version of MUI.

  @{fg shine}v1.68
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed the initial file in the Add File requester.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed FileCleaner that converted the '.' on extensions even
     when extensions were set to be excluded.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Some of the File Cleaner settings wasn't reloaded from prefs.

  @{fg shine}v1.67
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} When saving or exporting the list of files the file requester
     would sometimes not display files and silently use the file
     pattern filter hiding files incorrectly.

  @{fg shine}v1.66
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added an ID3v2 plugin! Now it is possible to extract a few tags
     from not only ID3v1 tags, but also the more extensive ID3v2 tags.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now all requesters will open on the same screen as MultiRen.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed the MP3-Info plugin. It sometimes couldn't skip an ID3v2
     tag correctly and was unable to read the MP3 info from the file.

  @{fg shine}v1.65
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added the ability to see the total file size of all files in the
     Info window. You can find the Info window in the Project menu.
     Very useful when collecting many files from different directories
     to transfer to a limited storage such as a CD-R or MP3/USB stick.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The file size for each file can also be selected for the list
     just as the filename lengths can.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Exporting to a textfile using the Custom way with columns (using %t)
     on multiple lines did not work correctly.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The tools list has been reorganized in alphabetic order.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Went over all help-bubbles and corrected spelling and made them a
     bit more understandable. Please also remember that the documentation
     is quite extensive.

  @{fg shine}v1.64
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added the menu option "Renamed files are Changed" in case
     you edit some filenames, renamed, save the list, then undo
     rename and then reload the saved list. Now all files would
     look renamed, but they are not, since you undid the rename.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed typo "Lenght".

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added some stack.

  @{fg shine}v1.63
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug which caused Unsort to malfunction if a list was
     loaded, sorted and then unsort was attempted.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Removed the requester asking to save a v1.0 compatible list.
     There is no need for this requester. MultiRen can still load
     v1.0 lists though.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} While borrowing code from MultiRen to TheMPegEncGUI I
     noticed a small bug that when picking a percent char to a
     format string only one percent char was copied, which kind of
     counteracts the whole point of having it as a special char :)

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} All european charactes had disappeared from the popdown menu
     in preferences. This was most likely cause by the texteditor
     past inability to handle 8-bit ASCII.

  @{fg shine}v1.62
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Apparently I had to re-introduce that stack-hack I removed
     in the last version, but this time with a version check so
     that it doesn't get executed if running V50+ (OS4).

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a few more options to the File Cleaner.

  @{fg shine}v1.61
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The File Cleaner now makes it possible to change space and
     underscore to the special white space character which is
     slightly longer than normal space in some fonts. It has
     ASCII value 160 and can be typed with Alt+Spacebar.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The File Cleaner now makes it possible to change normal hyphens
     (-) to a dashes () which has ASCII value 173 and are slightly
     longer than hyphens in some fonts which can make the files
     look better. Dashes can be typed with Alt+n.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now sorting has been extended to include more ways to sort
     file comments and paths.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Removed some kind of stack-hack proposed by someone. This
     hack doesn't work on OS4, or with EC3.3, which caused MultiRen
     to crash on exit.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Removed an astonishing amount of hits revealed by OS4's
     memory-protection :-)

  @{fg shine}v1.6
  ~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now it's possible to sort by the value of numbers, not
     just by characters. This means that "9-.." will come before
     "10-..". With the old (still available) character sort
     10 would come before 9 because "1" comes before "9".

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can sort the memo list in the Renplacer tool.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Some tools could hange with the gauge open if used on an
     empty list, like f.ex. the "Import a text file" feature.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Adding files shuffled only worked when adding files
     explicitly, not when adding a directory or recursive
     directory.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now it's also possible to load a list and get the files
     in the list shuffled with themselves or also with the
     files already in the list!
     NOTE: These shuffle functions are very handy when you
           want to have random playlists, or random picture
           lists or something. Just add files, shuffle, and
           export as text.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} I forgot one allocation object when I made the list
     adding and clearing faster in v1.53. Now I put the last
     object in the memory pool too and clearing a list of
     6000 entries is now made in a fraction of a second on
     a 060/50 compared to several seconds in v1.53 and almost
     halv a minute in v1.52 and earlier.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now there's a function for deleting duplicates of files.
     Useful when dealing with paths and files during creation
     of scripts for example.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} When fixing duplicates with ".. add ~N .." an actual
     number is added, not just a character.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} When using custom strings in the Text Export window or
     the File Comment tool you can not specify  how much of
     the end of a string you want to skip. Ex: %o[10,-3]
     would start to read the Old name at character 10 and
     read to the end but exclude the last 3 characters.
     Useful to remove extension on filenames with variable
     length when using a custom string.

  @{fg shine}v1.54
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a function to the Adaptor tool so that is possible to
     control what character the Adaptor should put the lengthener
     character around when prolonging a filename.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now the filename length also displays the length of the file
     comment (which cannot be more than 80 characters in AmigaDOS).
     The format is now <filename_length;comment_length> in the
     window. Also, the file comment gets /italic/ in the main lister
     if it exceeds 79 characters.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added the operator %t for use in the text export and file
     comment generation tools. This stands for tab. Whenever a %t
     is encountered a tab stop is set there which gets determind
     by the longest string up to the %t. Many %t's can be used in
     an export string.
     This way very nice columnized text files and file comments
     can be produced!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The memo list handling (in the RenPlacer, File Comment and
     Text Export tools) now saves the memo lists immediately when
     stored or removed if the checkmark in prefs is set.
     This makes it easier to not forget to save then when quitting
     the proram :)

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Updated the ID3-Tag plugin so that it always returns two
     digits for the track number. F.ex. 01,02,03...10,11,etc
     instead of 1,2,3...10,11 which makes it look nicer.

  @{fg shine}v1.53
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Adding files and loading a list is now more than twice as fast
     and clearing the list/exiting the program with files in the
     list is about 4 times faster!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} New plugin: Quoted Printable. It converts %20 etc to real
     characters.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} I gave the Extension Editor a major overhaul and I hope I made
     it more useful, atleast its functions should be consistent
     now and not so vague as before.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added some new extensions to the list of default extensions
     for the Extension Editor.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} I broke the code for dropping icons and shift-click adding
     items at start a couple of versions ago, now I restored the
     code again. I thouth that everthing was directories.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Some people reported the File Cleaner tool crashed. This might
     be fixed now as I found something in it that could have
     triggered a bug in the compiler!

  @{fg shine}v1.52
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Included the Substitute Generator into MultiRen. This should
     have been done a long time ago but it just didn't happen..

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a plugin: NGPTool. This helps renaming Neo-Geo Pocket
     rom files!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Broke a function in the Renplacer in the last release when
     renaming using single wildcard. It could cause the renplacer
     to hang.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed another bug in the Renplacer when renaming with single
     wildcard: If a string didn't match (and therefor shouldn't be
     affected) it was instead replaced by the source, e.g. the old
     name instead of being left as it was.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Made a couple of changes to the "Export list as text"-functions.
     Now it's possible to use a custom string just as in the
     File Comment tool. You can still use it as before and this
     has been made even more simple!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Custom string in the File Comment tool and the Text Export
     can now be save as the Renplacer strings can using that simple
     Store, Remove and popdown menu functions!

  @{fg shine}v1.51
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   I don't know what happened to v1.51?! ;)

  @{fg shine}v1.5
  ~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Requester was always opened on default pubscreen, not MultiRen's
     screen if this was defined to something other than default
     pubscreen.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Plugins are now automatically selected to be used when you
     select the plugins page in the renplacer the first time.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Made a new plugin for renaming PSID files! This was
     originally made by Fabrizio "Lanch" Bartoloni.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added functionality to the File Comment tool! It's now even
     more flexible when using the Custom source. You can use it
     to nicen up filenames too, not only file comments!

  @{fg shine}v1.49
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed two bugs in Renplacer/Find and one in Renplacer/Replace.
     Find screwed up a variable and acted random. Both interpreted
     the Source (Path,Old name etc) wrong.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added some functionality to the Numberer tool. Now you can
     easily add, remove or change the separator character used
     between the filename and the number without messing with
     the Renplacer.

  @{fg shine}v1.48
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed some problems with the Adaptor tool.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} You can now use Path as source in the Renplacer.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} A single wildcard in the Renplacer will now recognise any
     string, not just non-empty ones.

  @{fg shine}v1.47
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The Info window crashed badly. Fixed!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now it is possible to add files shuffled!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} A user found some flaws in the plugin template
     file template.mrp.c.

  @{fg shine}v1.46
  ~~~~~@{fg text}

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can save patterns in the Renplacer so that you don't
     have to re-type them every time if you often use a few different
     patterns!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The Filecomment tool is now more powerful when using the custom
     string. You can write f.ex: '%n[2;5]' to use 5 chars from offset
     2 in the New name instead of just the whole New name as before
     with just '%n'!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a new status column for the file comments!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The file pattern in the file requester was remembered internally
     but not reused in the requester when opening the requester again.
     This have been fixed.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a few bugs..

  @{fg shine}v1.45
  ~~~~~@{fg text}

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now the Adaptor has a switch so that filenames can be just
     cut down instead of "compressed" as before.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now there's a switch in the prefs to make MultiRen also set
     the file comments when renaming. (I ususally forget to set
     the comments on my files when I'm editing both filenames
     and comments :))

  @{fg shine}v1.44
  ~~~~~@{fg text}

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can decide what entry MultiRen should sort secondly by!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The left offset also affected the secondly sorted entries,
     now it doesn't.

  @{fg shine}v1.43
  ~~~~~@{fg text}

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can start MultiRen with filenames as argument or
     by shift-clicking on icons in workbench!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can hide the Old name column!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug which made the Renplacer/Replace function to
     hang sometimes.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The Sort tool can now be nicely shrunk if you want :)

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug with the Fast Find find next function.

  @{fg shine}v1.42
  ~~~~~@{fg text}

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can get your .info files renamed automatically!
     Just set a flag in the prefs.

  @{fg shine}v1.41
  ~~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added an offset feature to the Sort tool.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added an offset feature to the "Import a textfile"-window.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now it's possible to re-read filecomment from all enabled files.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can rename directories too by dropping them on the
     main window!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug that caused the Renplacer/Rename to always use indexed
     wildcards in some situations.

  @{fg shine}v1.4
  ~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now using NList(view).mcc for the main listview and BetterString.mcc
     for some strings!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can load a plain text-file to the list, not only .mrl files!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a little info window that tells you things about the files.
     Open it from the menu: "Open info window".

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Enhanced and bugfixed some plugins! Some plugins now has some useful
     settings to edit. Press the "?" in the plugin list.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} There is one more page in the prefs window with some nice settings!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} "Map file to filenames" has changed to "Import a text file" but
     it's function and purpose is the same. (This is not where you
     "load a text file" as said above.)

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} I added an easy to use find function that you can use if you
     just want to find some string somewhere in the list and don't
     want to mess with the more advanced find function in the Replacer.
     Press "f" in the main window!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can change the path for the files! Just select them and
     look into the Edit menu.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can sort by extensions.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The extension list has been extended and the Extension Editor tool
     has been improved on some points.

  @{fg shine}v1.3
  ~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now MultiRen supports plugins!!!
     With plugins, the flexibility of MultiRen becomes endless!
     Currently there are a few plugins that can extract the "real"
     name of music modules, 8SVX- and AIFF-samples. There's a text-
     extracting utility which is exellent for making file-comments
     out of the first line of text-files.
     I'm awaiting a plugin for dragging the ID3-tags out of MP3-
     files so you easily can rename all you 01.mp3, 02.mp3... to
     their real names!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The edit-string for manual rename now has the spacebar
     as hotkey!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The Map to Filenames has got some new features!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} 


  @{fg shine}v1.2
  ~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} MultiRen became Key-mail Ware which means that you have
     to send me an e-mail with your name to get a key-file
     so you can get rid of all annoying requesters and shit! :-)

     It's absolutely free, I just want to know how many cool
     users I've got ;-))
     Your name will ofcource not be used for anything else
     than to create your personal keyfile which will be sent
     back to you ASAP.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Did you ever think of the idea to rename a couple of files
     whos new names is in a textfile??
     Now you can do it the easy way!  Just map a textfile to
     your filenames in MultiRen and that's it!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can use the FileComment tool to edit (add, remove,
     change, improve) your filecomments!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now the extensions in the Extension Editor can be saved!


  @{fg shine}v1.1
  ~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can use the Numberer tool to number your files
     in very flexible ways!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The text-export has got new features which makes you able
     to put f.ex commands in the filelist you create so that
     you can execute it as a dos-script f.ex!


@endnode

@node Bugs " Bugs"

    @{fg shine}@{b}Bugs@{ub}
    ~~~~@{fg text}

 *I have been notified that plugins, especially written in C/C++
  can hang or crash sometimes.
  - This can possibly have been fixed now.

 *Some people have reported that the File Cleaner tool crashes.
  I can't reproduce this bug and I can't find anything in the code
  either. I'm waiting for test results from you!
  - Possibly fixed now. Might have been a compiler bug.

 *The sort routine might hang if you select second or third entry
  to the same as the main entry you are sorting by and are using the
  left offset.

 *The gauge behaves strangely if you are processing the list and many
  files are Disabled. Nothing is wrong though...

 *The adaptor might remove, or add, a few characters more than it
  have to to make the filenames look nicer after they have been
  adapted.
  This will ofcourse not happen if you set to adapt to exact size.


  If you would find other bugs, do not hesitate to contact
  @{"me" link Author} at daniel@onyxsoft.se and tell me what the problem is!


@endnode

@node Future "What will come..!"

    @{fg shine}@{b}Future@{ub}
    ~~~~~~@{fg text}

  * A Version plugin. Would anyone be kind enough to make one??

  * Any other plugin? Get on coding, or send me a mail :)


@endnode

